Modern State Management Decision Guide | IMAGE by notebooklm
The problem nobody names
NgRx isn’t the problem. NgRx overuse is.
For years, NgRx was the default answer to any non-trivial state in Angular. The result is that most Angular codebases use NgRx for things that don’t need NgRx — and now have Actions, Reducers, and Effects managing the state of a dropdown.
The arrival of Signals didn’t make NgRx obsolete. It made visible what was already wrong: most of the state you put in NgRx didn’t need to be there. The question isn’t “NgRx or Signals?” — it’s “does this state need to be global?”
The honest answer, most of the time, is no.
The three-layer rule: Angular 22 with Signals forces a decision that used to be postponed: where does this state live? The answer defines the tool. Component state → signal(). Feature state → signalStore(). Genuinely cross-cutting application state → classic NgRx Store. Each level above the previous one has a cost. Justify the cost before moving up.
Signals don’t replace NgRx. They replace the NgRx overproduction that became the default.

Layer 1 — Pure signal
When signal() solves everything — and why you don't need anything else
Local and derived state doesn’t need a store. This is the most underestimated case in modern Angular. Most of what lives in NgRx in a typical codebase should be here.
d — only recalculates when users or filter change
filtered = computed(() => {
const q = this.filter().toLowerCase();
return (this.users.value() ?? [])
.filter(u => u.name.toLowerCase().includes(q));
}); // No NgModule. No Actions. No Effects. No Reducers.
// No subscribe. No takeUntilDestroyed.
}
// Situations where pure signal is ENOUGH:
// ✓ Loading / error from an HTTP request
// ✓ Local filters and search
// ✓ Pagination of a single list
// ✓ Open/closed state of modals and dropdowns
// ✓ Forms with Signal Forms
// ✓ Counter, toggle, tab selection
// ✓ Any state only one component consumes
Warning sign: if you’re creating an @ngrx/store Action for something only one component uses, you're paying an abstraction cost without receiving any benefit. Component state belongs to the component. When another component needs that state, that's when you decide where to promote it — not before.
Layer 2 — NgRx SignalStore
The middle ground Angular needed
NgRx SignalStore is what you use when state needs to survive beyond a single component, but doesn’t need Redux. An injectable service, built with Signals, scoped to a route or feature.
What you wrote with classic NgRx (products feature):

• products.actions.ts — loadProducts, loadProductsSuccess, loadProductsFailure...

• products.reducer.ts — switch/case with manual immutability

• products.selectors.ts — selectProducts, selectLoading, selectError...

• products.effects.ts — ofType, switchMap, catchError, map

• products.module.ts — StoreModule.forFeature()

• 4+ files, 200+ lines for a simple listing feature
What you write with SignalStore:

• A single products.store.ts file

• State, computed, and methods in the same place

• No Actions, no Reducers, no separate Selectors

• Injectable like any other service

• Route scope — clears when the user navigates away
SignalStore in practice — complete products feature
import { inject } from '@angular/core';
import { rxMethod } from '@ngrx/signals/rxjs-interop';
import { tapResponse } from '@ngrx/operators';
import {
patchState, signalStore,
withComputed, withMethods, withState
} from '@ngrx/signals';
import {
addEntities, removeEntity, updateEntity,
withEntities
} from '@ngrx/signals/entities';
import { pipe, switchMap } from 'rxjs';
import { ProductsService } from './products.service';
import { Product } from './product.model';interface ProductsExtra {
loading: boolean;
error: string | null;
filter: string;
page: number;
}
export const ProductsStore = signalStore(
withEntities<Product>(),
withState<ProductsExtra>({
loading: false,
error: null,
filter: '',
page: 1,
}),
withComputed(({ entities, filter }) => ({
filteredProducts: computed(() => {
const q = filter().toLowerCase();
return entities().filter(p =>
p.name.toLowerCase().includes(q) ||
p.sku.toLowerCase().includes(q)
);
}),
totalItems: computed(() => entities().length),
})),
withMethods((store, svc = inject(ProductsService)) => ({
setFilter(term: string) {
patchState(store, { filter: term, page: 1 });
},
load: rxMethod<void>(
pipe(
switchMap(() => {
patchState(store, { loading: true, error: null });
return svc.getAll().pipe(
tapResponse({
next: (products) => patchState(store, addEntities(products)),
error: (e: Error) => patchState(store, { loading: false, error: e.message }),
finalize: () => patchState(store, { loading: false }),
})
);
})
)
),
remove(id: number) {
patchState(store, removeEntity(id));
svc.delete(id).subscribe(); // optimistic update
},
}))
);
// Usage in component:
// store = inject(ProductsStore)
// store.load() → triggers loading
// store.setFilter('laptop') → filters synchronously
// store.filteredProducts() → computed signal
// store.loading() → reactive boolean
Cutting boilerplate: reusable signalStoreFeature
A community developer reported cutting 40% of their NgRx Signal Store boilerplate by extracting reusable features. The pattern: encapsulate common behavior in signalStoreFeature().
// features/with-request-status.ts
export function withRequestStatus() {
return signalStoreFeature(
withState({ loading: false, error: null as string | null }),
withMethods((store) => ({
setPending: () => patchState(store, { loading: true, error: null }),
setFulfilled: () => patchState(store, { loading: false }),
setError: (msg: string) => patchState(store, { loading: false, error: msg }),
}))
);
}// Usage — clean store, no repeating loading/error everywhere:
export const ProductsStore = signalStore(
withEntities<Product>(),
withRequestStatus(), // ← 8 lines become 1
withMethods((store, svc = inject(ProductsService)) => ({
load: rxMethod<void>(pipe(
switchMap(() => {
store.setPending();
return svc.getAll().pipe(
tapResponse({
next: (ps) => { patchState(store, addEntities(ps)); store.setFulfilled(); },
error: (e: Error) => store.setError(e.message),
})
);
})
)),
}))
);
Layer 3 — Classic NgRx Store
When classic NgRx is still the right choice
The classic NgRx Store isn’t dead. It found its real place: genuinely global state, with auditing, DevTools, and coordination between independent features.
The real criterion: ask this question before creating a classic NgRx store: does more than one feature need to react to this state without knowing where it came from? If yes — auth, permissions, notifications, tenant configuration — classic NgRx is still the right instrument.
// ✅ Case 1: Authentication — the entire app reacts
export const AuthActions = createActionGroup({
source: 'Auth',
events: {
'Login Success': props<{ user: User; token: string }>(),
'Logout': emptyProps(),
'Token Expired': emptyProps(),
}
});// ✅ Case 2: Global notifications — cross-cutting by definition
export const NotifActions = createActionGroup({
source: 'Notifications',
events: {
'Add': props<{ message: string; type: 'success' | 'error' | 'info' }>(),
'Remove': props<{ id: string }>(),
}
});
// Any feature can dispatch. Only NotificationsComponent consumes. Zero coupling.
// ✅ Case 3: DevTools and compliance auditing
// In financial and healthcare apps, every state change needs an audit trail.
// NgRx DevTools + Actions give you this for free.
// ❌ Where classic NgRx is no longer worth it:
// - State of a listing screen → SignalStore with withEntities()
// - Loading from a single HTTP request → local signal() or httpResource()
// - Table filters and sorting → local signal()
// - Shopping cart of a single feature → SignalStore
⚠️ The most common anti-pattern: creating an NgRx Action for every CRUD operation in a feature. loadProducts, loadProductsSuccess, loadProductsFailure, selectProduct — all Actions for state that never leaves the feature. SignalStore solves in 30 lines what those Actions solve in 200.
How to migrate without a big bang
The right migration is not a rewrite. It’s a progressive redirection of new code toward the correct abstraction level, while what already works keeps working.
Step 1 — State audit:
List all current NgRx stores and classify each as “local component”, “feature”, or “real global”. Most will go to “feature” — and that’s your opportunity to simplify without immediate risk.
Step 2 — Convert local BehaviorSubjects first:
If any component uses BehaviorSubject + async pipe for local state, replace it with signal(). Zero risk — component scope, no side effects. Familiarizes the team with the API before any larger refactoring.
Step 3 — Migrate new features to SignalStore:
Don’t touch stores that work. For each new feature or module, use SignalStore + withEntities(). In 2-3 sprints, the team gains fluency without risking regressions in existing code.
Step 4 — Migrate existing feature stores opportunistically:
When a feature requires significant maintenance, migrate its store to SignalStore. Not as an isolated task — embedded in feature work. This ensures the migration has immediate value. Add the ESLint rule in the same PR — while the directory is being touched, resistance is zero.
Automation: when migration depends on human review, it regresses
A migration that depends on team discipline regresses. One that blocks in CI always blocks. The ESLint rule transforms Step 3 from a team policy into a technical contract.
// tools/eslint-rules/no-ngrx-actions-in-features.js
// Blocks createAction/createActionGroup in src/app/features/**
// Classic NgRx is reserved for src/app/core/store/ and src/app/store/
module.exports = {
meta: {
type: 'problem',
docs: {
description: 'Prohibits createAction/createActionGroup in feature directories. '
+ 'Use NgRx SignalStore (withMethods + patchState) for feature state.',
url: 'https://blense.fun/angular-producao-01',
},
messages: {
noActionsInFeature:
'createAction/createActionGroup is not allowed in features/ ({{ path }}). '
+ 'Use SignalStore for feature state. '
+ 'Classic NgRx is reserved for src/app/core/store/ and src/app/store/.',
},
},
create(context) {
const filePath = context.getFilename();
if (!filePath.includes('/src/app/features/')) return {};
const BLOCKED = new Set(['createAction', 'createActionGroup']);
return {
ImportDeclaration(node) {
if (node.source.value !== '@ngrx/store') return;
node.specifiers.forEach(spec => {
if (spec.type === 'ImportSpecifier' && BLOCKED.has(spec.imported.name)) {
context.report({
node: spec,
messageId: 'noActionsInFeature',
data: { path: filePath.split('/src/app/')[1] },
});
}
});
},
};
},
};// .eslintrc.json
{
"plugins": ["local-rules"],
"rules": {
"local-rules/no-ngrx-actions-in-features": "error",
"local-rules/no-store-inject-in-feature-components": "warn"
}
}# .github/workflows/pr-checks.yml
